    intro: "Low levels of sebum in dry skin make it susceptible to irritation. The skin's inability to retain moisture gives it a dry appearance. If no moisturiser or skin cream is applied after washing, it usually feels \"tight\" and uncomfortable. Skin that is severely dry and dehydrated will crack and chap.",
    content: "1. Wash your face gently at least twice per day: Use a mild, alcohol- free, nonfoaming cleanser on your face twice day and right after you've worked up a sweat. Your skin can be repaired with products that include linoleic acid or stearic acid, which are both present in argan oil and shea butter, respectively. If you have sensitive skin, wash in the evening with a cleanser and simply rinse the rest of the time.<br/><br/>2. Maintain Moisture : Keep your natural oils in place. Your skin naturally creates oils to protect it from the environment and keep it from drying out. But throughout the day, you engage in numerous activities that remove these natural oils. Your bathing habits pose the biggest risk to the natural defence system of your skin. Your skin is at risk from both soaps that remove too much oil from your skin and water that is too hot. Shower at the coolest setting you can tolerate, and only use soaps that say \"sensitive skin\" or contain moisturizers.<br/><b>Precautions:</b> Make cautious not to bathe too frequently or for too long. Both have the potential to remove too much of your natural oil. Take only one shower every day, for no longer than 10-15 minutes. Bathe only every other day if you can.<br/><br/>3. Use a moisturising soap devoid of allergens: Use hypoallergenic (fragrance-free) moisturising soap when washing your hands. Then, while your hands are still damp, apply a moisturising cream. Try using a non-soap cleansing cream or shower gel in the shower or bath, and only use soap in places like the groyne and armpits when necessary. Avoid using pumice stones and loofahs. Rinse well, then pat yourself dry.<br/><br/>4. Use a humidifier: Indoor air that is hot and dry can parch delicate skin and make itchiness and peeling worse. You can add moisture to the air in your home by using a portable humidifier or one that is connected to your furnace. <br/><br/>5. Pick materials that are gentle on your skin:Cotton and other natural fabrics help your skin to breathe. Despite being natural, wool can occasionally irritate even healthy skin. Use laundry detergents free of dyes and fragrances, which can both irritate your skin. The word \"free\" is frequently used in the names of these products. <br/><br/>6. Relieve itchiness: Apply a clean, cool, wet cloth to the itchy area if dry skin is to blame. Applying an anti-itch lotion or ointment with at least 1% hydrocortisone may also be an option. Consult your doctor or a dermatologist about developing a customised skin care regimen depending on your skin type and any existing skin conditions if these steps fail to relieve your symptoms or if they worsen.",
