    intro: "Are you confused by the supermarket's lengthy aisle of shampoos and conditioners? We comprehend. You can have a cold sweat trying to select the best decision for your hair type. <br/>The fact is that every person's hair is different, just like every person, so there is no \"one-size-fits-all\" shampoo. To choose the one that will make your hair beautiful, shining, and healthy, you may, however, benefit from knowing your hair type and needs. To help you choose the best shampoo, we have outlined everything you need to know about the various hair types and their requirements in this post.",
    content: "1. Regular Hair <br/>You should count yourself lucky if you have low-maintenance hair, but even these require upkeep. So, choose sulfate-free shampoos that are appropriate for all hair types. Without removing any of the moisture and natural oils from your strands, this will hydrate, smoothen, and detangle. <br/><br/>2. For the dry, damaged or chemically treated hair <br/>Your hair's lengths can be prone to dryness and brittleness by nature. Additionally, if you've used chemical treatments to colour or straighten your hair, your hair may be more vulnerable to damage because it will be more sensitive to environmental pressures like pollution or photodamage. To nourish your damaged locks, use a shampoo that is protein-fortified and hair-strengthening. Amino acids and soy extracts are excellent for keeping coloured hair. To avoid drying out and colour loss, be careful to choose sulfate-free choices. <br/><br/>3. Rough Hair <br/>You need to wash your hair more frequently if you have rough hair. Choose a creamy, moisturising shampoo if you plan to use excessive amounts of hair product. Such ingredients like shea, coconut, or olive butter should be sought for. You should pick your conditioner carefully in addition to your shampoo. You should pick a conditioner that is especially moisturising since it will coat your hair and keep moisture inside, giving you soft hair. <br/><br/>4. Frizzy Hair <br/>Choose moisturising, low-foaming, and sulfate-free shampoos if you want to prevent frizz. To replace the moisture lost, search for silicones and proteins that have been added to your shampoo. <br/><br/>5. Fine Hair <br/>If you have thin hair, you should use thickening products, but they shouldn't be too creamy or heavy. Choose goods that will give you a lot of volume. For the best benefits, you should also wash your hair frequently. <br/><br/>6. Oily Hair <br/>Use a shampoo that removes oil from the hair strands, tones the scalp, and avoids clogged follicles if you have oily hair. Choose goods with high concentrations of astringent and thickening components like panthenol and wheat protein. <br/><br/>7. Coloured Hair <br/>Chemically treated hair need more tender loving care. Choose a shampoo that keeps your hair's radiance intact, shields it from the sun, and stops the colour from fading. It is preferable if your items contain UV filters to stop the colour from fading. One of the most important steps in your hair care routine is washing your hair with the appropriate shampoo. Shampoos have an impact on both your scalp and individual hair strands. <br/>As a result, you should determine what kind of scalp and hair you have and select a shampoo accordingly. To address your unique hair difficulties, a number of shampoos and conditioners are readily available on the market. To choose the best shampoo, you can do your own research or speak with a professional.",
