    id: 12,
    title: "Can CoViD worsen your skin problems? Read to know.",
    image: "./blogs/can-covid-worsen-your-skin.jpg",
    slug: "can-covid-worsen-your-skin",
    intro: "We are becoming more and more aware that COVID-19 affects the body in ways other than just the lungs as the pandemic spreads. The skin is a part of that. There have been complaints of various rashes, \"COVID toes,\" hair loss, and other skin issues. While some skin signs emerge later or in cases of more severe disease, others first show up shortly after an infection. Most people improve over time. Additionally, researchers are starting to figure out what triggers various skin problems, such as hormones or the body's immune response to an infection.",
    content: "From the most typical to the least, here are some of these signs:<br/><br/>1. Several flat red areas and numerous small, spreading red pimples: These'maculopapular eruptions' are linked to more serious illness. <br/><br/>2. Redness of the eye whites: This conjunctivitis is more prevalent in more advanced disease and in disease that is more severe. <br/><br/>3. \"COVID toes,\" or symptoms resembling chilblains: These can affect either the hands or the feet, or both at once. Small blisters or pustules can occasionally be seen along with the reddish-purple discoloured skin, which can also be unpleasant and itchy. Children are more likely to get these chilblain-like lesions because they frequently manifest later in the illness, following other symptoms. <br/><br/>4. Hives or urticaria are blotchy, elevated red lumps or pink or red, itchy rashes (wheals). Pinhead to dinner plate size, they come in a variety of shapes. Swellings may come and go, but they often go away in one area between minutes to hours. Hives often disappear in ten days. They appear simultaneously with other symptoms, affect people of all ages, and are linked to diseases that are more severe. <br/><br/>5. Vesicular eruptions, also known as water blisters, are tiny fluid- filled micro-blisters that can develop at any time and are frequently found on the hands. Middle-aged patients typically experience pain. The blisters are indicative of an illness with a medium severity and last slightly over 10 days. <br/><br/><b>How do I know if my skin rash is COVID-19? </b><br/>Compare your skin symptoms to the pictures in this post if you have any concerns. Then, for more guidance, schedule a telemedicine session with your general practitioner or dermatologist. You might spread diseases. Get tested, then isolate yourself until you learn the results. Your GP or COVID clinic will be able to plan your care if you're feeling under the weather.",
