    slug: "5-most-harmful-chemicals-that-are-being-used-in-face-wash",
    intro: "\"You are what you eat,\" is a proverb that you've probably heard. The same idea also applies to your skin: Whatever you put on it gets absorbed right into your body. Knowing what you're putting into your body is important because your skin is the greatest organ in your body. <br/><br/>However, if you've ever flipped over the label of your preferred facial cleanser, you may have found a lengthy list of unfamiliar components. The cosmetics business includes a variety of compounds in its products, from sulphates to parabens; some are helpful, while others may be detrimental. And many of them may possibly be harming your appearance rather than improving it. Discover five ingredients you should stay away from by reading on.",
    content: "1. Phthalate <br/>Based on the number and arrangement of the carbon molecules, there are various types of phthalates. Because they have several uses in the cosmetics business, phthalates are widely used. Phthalates are utilised in a variety of ways, including (1) as a solubilizer to dissolve chemicals, (2) as a humectant to keep items from drying out, (3) as an emollient to soften skin, and (4) as a plasticizer to make polymers more flexible. Sadly, there are connections between exposure to specific phthalates at high levels and male reproductive health. In addition to posing a risk to individuals, many water treatment facilities are unable to completely remove phthalates from drinking water. <br/><br/>2. Sodium Lauryl Sulfate <br/>You know the sensation of being spotlessly clean after washing your face? According to Jody Levine, M.D., assistant clinical instructor of dermatology at Mount Sinai Hospital in New York City, sodium lauryl sulphate, a common component added to face wash to make it foam, is to blame. She adds that many other personal care items, including shampoo, frequently include it. But sodium lauryl sulphate isn't simply found in the cosmetics section; it's also a component of engine degreasers, garage floor cleaners, and car washes. <br/>The issue with sodium lauryl sulphate is that it depletes the skin (and scalp, in the case of shampoo), both of which are really in need of natural oils for protection, from these oils. Levine says that it \"may be highly irritating, especially if a person is allergic to it.\" According to studies, even small levels of allergens in items might result in adverse reactions. The body also produces extra oil (the same thing you're trying to get rid of) to make up for the loss of the skin's natural, protective oil. <br/><br/>3. Fragrances <br/>A personal care product's perfumes are just included to give it a more pleasant smell. Most fragrances are semi-volatile in order to deliver smells quickly. There are valid reasons why you might want to use items without them even though they serve no practical purposes besides providing a pleasant smell. Some fragrance-making ingredients, particularly petroleum-based ones, have been linked to headaches, skin conditions, and other health problems. If you don't want to use a fragrance-free product, check for one with the label \"fragrance-free,\" as \"unscented\" items frequently still have fragrances in them. <br/><br/>4. Parabens <br/>The paraben family of chemicals includes a wide range of distinct chemical substances. The length of its carbon side chain is the key  characteristic that sets these related molecules apart. By keeping items stable throughout a wide variety of temperatures, parabens are used by the cosmetic and skin care sector to assist extend the shelf life of their products. Additionally, parabens have antibacterial qualities. Paraben exposure can have negative effects on male reproductive, similar to phthalate exposure. According to studies, high degrees of physical contact with paraben reduced sperm counts in male animals. <br/><br/>5. Oils <br/>Ingredients generated from petroleum and mineral oils are found in many products. They are inexpensive, odourless, and never go bad, making them a favourite among cosmetic makers. Manufacturers might use this as a hydrating element in cleansers, according to Levine. Additionally, while some types of oil can clog pores and cause breakouts, others do in fact add moisture. Levine advises employing oil-free cleansers unless your skin is exceptionally dry. Make sure the product doesn't contain propylene glycol, paraffin, mineral oil, butylene glycol, isopropyl alcohol, or petrolatum by checking the ingredients list. Instead, opt for pure plant oils that are natural and rich in nutrition without clogging your pores. <br/><br/>We hope that the information provided here will be helpful to you as you search for the top men's face wash. It's crucial to maintain good facial and physical wellness. The easiest approach to achieve this is to stay away from face washes that contain possibly dangerous substances. Because of this, Tiege Hanley takes great satisfaction in employing the greatest skin-care ingredients on the market. For instance, we utilise ammonium lauryl sulphate, a significantly superior ingredient, in our face cleanser instead of SLS and SLES (ALS). ALS is considerably more effective in removing dirt and filth from the surface layers of your facial skin without running the risk of the product penetrating and damaging the much more sensitive underlying layers of skin.",
